Identities with combinatorial proofs.
Many identities involving binomial coefficients can be proved by combinatorial means. For example, the following identity for nonnegative integers formula_65 (which reduces to () when "q" = 1):
can be given a double counting proof as follows. The left side counts the number of ways of selecting a subset of ["n"] = {1, 2, …, n} with at least "q" elements, and marking "q" elements among those selected. The right side counts the same parameter, because there are formula_67 ways of choosing a set of "q" marks and they occur in all subsets that additionally contain some subset of the remaining elements, of which there are formula_68
In the Pascal's rule
both sides count the number of "k"-element subsets of ["n"] with the right hand side ﬁrst grouping them into those that contain element "n" and those that do not.
The identity () also has a combinatorial proof. The identity reads
Suppose you have formula_71 empty squares arranged in a row and you want to mark (select) "n" of them. There are formula_72 ways to do this. On the other hand, you may select your "n" squares by selecting "k" squares from among the first "n" and formula_73 squares from the remaining "n" squares; any "k" from 0 to "n" will work. This gives
Now apply () to get the result.
The identity (),
has the following combinatorial proof. The number formula_76 denotes the number of paths in a two-dimensional lattice from formula_77 to formula_78 using steps formula_79 and formula_80. This is easy to see: there are formula_81 steps in total and one may choose the formula_82 formula_79 steps. Now, replace each formula_80 step by a formula_85 step; note that there are exactly formula_82. Then one arrives at point formula_87 using steps formula_79 and formula_85. Doing this for all formula_82 between formula_91 and formula_92 gives all paths from formula_77 to formula_87 using steps formula_79 and formula_85. Clearly, there are exactly formula_97 such paths.
Sum of coefficients row.
The number of "k"-combinations for all "k", formula_98, is the sum of the "n"th row (counting from 0) of the binomial coefficients. These combinations are enumerated by the 1 digits of the set of base 2 numbers counting from 0 to formula_99, where each digit position is an item from the set of "n".
