This proves the binomial theorem.
Inductive proof.
Induction yields another proof of the binomial theorem (1). When "n" = 0, both sides equal 1, since "x"0 = 1 and formula_47.
Now suppose that (1) holds for a given "n"; we will prove it for "n" + 1.
For "j", "k" ≥ 0, let ["ƒ"("x", "y")] "jk" denote the coefficient of "x""j""y""k" in the polynomial "ƒ"("x", "y").
By the inductive hypothesis, ("x" + "y")"n" is a polynomial in "x" and "y" such that [("x" + "y")"n"] "j,k" is formula_48 if "j" + "k" = "n", and 0 otherwise.
